{
"summary_of_the_paper": "This paper introduces Synthetic Environments (SEs) and Reward Networks (RNs), neural network-based proxy models for training Reinforcement Learning (RL) agents. The authors propose a bi-level optimization scheme, where an inner loop trains an RL agent on the proxy, and an outer loop, using an evolution strategy, updates the SE or RN parameters based on the agent's performance in the real environment. SEs learn both state dynamics and rewards, acting as full environment proxies, while RNs learn to augment or replace rewards, serving as partial proxies. The research demonstrates that agents trained exclusively on learned SEs can solve corresponding real environments, and that both SEs and RNs enable more efficient agent training (fewer interactions) compared to training directly on the real environment. The paper also shows that these learned proxies are robust to hyperparameter variations and can transfer to unseen RL agents. Empirical results suggest that SEs achieve efficiency by learning informed representations that bias agents towards relevant states. The work evaluates these concepts on a range of classic control tasks and RL algorithms.",
"main_review": "This paper introduces a novel and promising approach to meta-learning proxy environments (Synthetic Environments, SEs) and reward functions (Reward Networks, RNs) for RL. The bi-level optimization scheme, where an outer evolution strategy optimizes the proxy based on agent performance in the real environment, is innovative and agent-agnostic. The work provides extensive empirical evidence across various control tasks and RL algorithms, consistently demonstrating significant efficiency gains for agent training, robustness to hyperparameter variations, and transferability to unseen agents. The qualitative analysis offering insights into how SEs learn informed state/reward representations is a valuable contribution.\n\nHowever, the approach has limitations. Learning full SEs is computationally demanding and currently does not scale to more complex environments like HalfCheetah. While generally robust, some agent transfer scenarios, particularly with TD3 on SEs, show instances of performance degradation or failures, warranting further investigation into their causes. The poor performance of the supervised model learning baseline in the appendix also limits its utility for a deeper comparison. Finally, the design of the RN objective function could be refined to encourage continuous improvement beyond task-solving thresholds.\n\nOverall, despite these limitations, the paper presents a strong, well-executed contribution with a novel concept and thorough empirical validation, opening exciting new research directions.",
"summary_of_the_review": "This paper introduces a novel approach for learning Synthetic Environments (SEs) and Reward Networks (RNs) as proxy models for RL agent training, utilizing a bi-level optimization strategy. The work demonstrates significant efficiency gains, robustness to hyperparameter changes, and transferability to unseen agents across various control tasks. Key strengths include the innovative meta-learning framework, comprehensive empirical evaluation, and qualitative analysis of how proxies learn informed representations. While the concept is highly promising, current limitations include the high computational cost of learning full SEs for complex environments and some observed performance degradation during agent transfer in specific scenarios. Overall, it's a strong contribution opening new research avenues.",
"recommendation": "8: accept, good submission"
}

{
    "summary_of_the_paper": "The paper introduces \"Visually-Informed Dereverberation of Audio (VIDA)\", a novel end-to-end approach for removing speech reverberation by leveraging both audio and visual observations. Recognizing that visual cues about room geometry, materials, and speaker location inform acoustic properties, VIDA employs a Visual Acoustics Network (VAN) to extract visual features, which are then fused with audio features within a UNet-based dereverberation module. The model is trained on a new large-scale dataset created using the SoundSpaces simulator, which acoustically renders speech in real-world 3D scanned environments, and is further validated on real-world recordings. Experiments demonstrate that VIDA achieves state-of-the-art performance across speech enhancement, automatic speech recognition, and speaker verification tasks, substantially outperforming audio-only methods and showing promising sim2real transfer capabilities.",
    "main_review": "The paper introduces VIDA, a highly original and well-executed approach to audio-visual dereverberation. The core idea of leveraging visual cues from the environment (geometry, materials, speaker location) to improve speech dereverberation is compelling and well-motivated, addressing an underconstrained audio-only problem. The proposed VIDA model, with its Visual Acoustics Network (VAN) and multi-modal UNet, effectively integrates RGB-D visual information with audio. The inclusion of a contrastive reverb-visual matching loss is a clever mechanism to enforce consistency between modalities. The authors meticulously construct a large-scale simulated dataset using SoundSpaces and Matterport3D, offering diverse acoustic environments and ground truth anechoic audio, and further validate on real-world recordings. Experiments demonstrate that VIDA consistently outperforms a range of strong audio-only baselines across three critical downstream tasks (speech enhancement, ASR, speaker verification), showing significant gains. Detailed ablations effectively highlight the contribution of each component, and insightful analyses of learned visual features (TSNE plots) are provided. The commitment to publicly release code and data ensures high reproducibility.\n\nMinor areas for improvement include clarifying the role of the UNet's predicted phase versus Griffin-Lim in reconstruction, as the paper notes Griffin-Lim performs better. A brief discussion on the challenges of adapting existing audio-visual speech enhancement/separation models as direct dereverberation baselines would strengthen the comparison section. While the \"w/o human mesh\" ablation shows human presence helps, further discussion on disentangling speaker location from subtle speaker-specific acoustic contributions (e.g., body shape) could be interesting. Finally, explicitly outlining strategies for further bridging the sim2real gap in future work would be beneficial.",
    "summary_of_the_review": "This paper presents VIDA, a highly original and well-executed approach to audio-visual dereverberation. The core idea of leveraging visual cues from the environment to improve speech dereverberation is compelling and well-motivated. The authors introduce a robust model architecture, meticulously curate a large-scale dataset, and conduct comprehensive experiments demonstrating significant improvements over audio-only baselines across multiple tasks. The paper's strengths in novelty, empirical validation, and reproducibility are substantial. Minor areas for improvement include clarifying phase handling during reconstruction and discussing the relation to other audio-visual enhancement tasks. Overall, this is a strong submission that opens a promising new direction for speech processing.",
    "recommendation": "10: strong accept, should be highlighted at the conference."
}

